TikTok hides unpleasant videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40 per cent of whom are under 18 years of age.
China / Reuters
TikTok, a Chinese social network, censorships videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet Independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong, relates The Guardian.
The documents before the publication state that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance) uses the application to advance China's foreign policy objectives abroad.
The bulk of the violations of China's policy fall under the “inflammation of hatred”.
In each case, TikTok places unpleasant publications in a context suitable for general rules so that the activities of the social network do not appear to be censorship.
For example, the prohibition of criticism of the socialist system of China falls under the general prohibition of “criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc.”.
A ban on the mention of incidents in Tiananmen Square or genocide in Cambodia falls under the “stirring of China's history or other countries”.
The document also contains a list of the prohibited names of the twenty “Foreign Leaders or Government Officials”, including the North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sena and Kim Jing Ein, the Indian policy of Mahatmu Gandhi, American Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, the Japanese Prime Minister Sinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Kin Hee, the President of Indonesia, Joko Vidodo and the Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi, as indicated in the document.
The prohibited material is divided into two categories, as stated in the document.
Publications in the first category are removed by social media administrators and may result in user lockdowns.
The second category of violations is not too severe: such publications remain on the website, but are limited to TikTok algorithms.
The representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: "We are now using a localized approach to the modernization, and we are also attracting independent local professionals."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says Co-founder Rustem Bogdanov’s Preducer Center.
The Preducer Centre is a Russian media company that formally cooperates with TikTok.
All of the bloggers of Preducer Center agree with the social media, but the user's material can be placed without agreement, and passed on to the Bogdans.
Asked if TikTok could speak about politics or Putin, the Bogdans responded positively and said that they had seen such publications.
Bogdanov agrees with the founder of Our Digital Roman Zaripov: “The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: there is no way to present shocking content that discriminates against words and so forth.”
But under these rules, any content that the modernists don't like can be subsumed, says Zarip.
Zaripova is another Russian partner, TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40 per cent of whom are under the age of 18.
By user agreement, TikTok may only be used by persons over 13.
Social media administrators test their age by artificial intelligence: Neurosthet analyzes faces and determines what kind of years a person looks like, tells Bogdan.
If the narossus decides that the user is younger, his account may be removed, he adds.
