In Chile, a telescope worth 1 billion euros began to be built
TASS reported this with reference to the European Southern Observatory (ESO) press service.
According to ESO, this week the construction of the building's dome, where the E-ELT telescope will be located, was officially launched, while the most expensive and ambitious ground astronomical project was being undertaken.
Its total value is estimated to exceed a billion euros.
Most of this money will be spent on the construction of equipment and the building of the observatory.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record large mirror, with a diameter of about 39 metres.
It will be collected from 798 hexagonal segments of 1.4 meters.
It's a huge mirror, and it's two supporting reflection surfaces that are 4.2 and 3.75 meters in diameter will help E-ELT get the first detailed photos of planets outside the solar system, stars in other galaxies, and look for Earth's doubles.
In addition, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the surrounding Sgr A*, a supermassive black hole in the center of the Milky Way.
Although the construction of the dome is only started, mirrors, scientific tools and other observatories have been developed by scientists, engineers and other specialists for three years, since the first E-ELT construction plans were announced.
The contract for the production of the main mirror, with a total value of about Euro400 million, was awarded by the German firm SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
